'''Abdul Ali''' ({{lang-bn|<U+0986><U+09AC><U+09CD><U+09A6><U+09C1><U+09B2> <U+099C><U+09BC><U+09BE><U+0995>}}; born 6 May 1969), best known as '''Ali Jacko''' ({{lang-bn|<U+0986><U+09B2><U+09BF> <U+099C><U+09BC><U+09BE><U+0995>}}), is an [[England|English]] former [[kickboxer]] who held world titles in the [[lightweight]] division. He also ran JKO Productions, which was part of the kickboxing promotion of [[Sky Sports]] and [[Channel 5]].

==Early life==
Ali was born in the [[East End of London|East End]] of [[[London]]. He is of [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]] descent<ref name="britbangla">{{cite web |url=http://www.britbangla.net/successprofiles.html#jacko|title=Jacko Ali|work=British Bengali Success Stories|publisher=BritBangla|date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> and lived in [[Bangladesh]] for six years.<ref name="alijacko">{{cite web |url=http://www.alijacko.com/alijacko-biodata.html|title=Bio Data|publisher=CA Foundation / Ali Jacko|date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> His late father<ref name="StraightDialogue5">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AbdkxGUo6hI|title=Ali Jacko|work=Straight Dialogue|publisher=[[Channel i]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Mohammed Chamak Ali was born in Farigow, Jawa Bazar, [[Chhatak Upazila|Chhatak]] in [[Sylhet Division]], [[East Pakistan]] (now [[Sunamganj District|Sunamganj]], [[Bangladesh]]).<ref name="StraightDialogue1">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VHknK34F83s|title=Ali Jacko|work=Straight Dialogue|publisher=[[Channel i]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref name="sylhetexpress">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.sylhetexpress.com/syfdiapicgel.php?SyfdianewsID=23628#newstop|title=<U+099B><U+09BE><U+09A4><U+0995><U+09C7><U+09B0> <U+09AA><U+09BE><U+0987><U+0997><U+09BE><U+0993><U+09AF><U+09BC><U+09C7> <U+09AC><U+09BF><U+09B0><U+09CB><U+09A7><U+09AA><U+09C1><U+09B0><U+09CD><U+09A3> <U+099C><U+09BE><U+09AF><U+09BC><U+0997><U+09BE><U+09B0> <U+09EA><U+09B0><U+09CD><U+09A5> <U+09AC><U+09BE><U+09B0><U+09C7><U+09B0><U+09AE><U+09A4> <U+09B0><U+09BE><U+09AF><U+09BC>|location=Sylhet|work= |publisher=''Sylhet Express.com''|date=1 August 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Ali has three younger brothers and two younger sisters.<ref name="StraightDialogue7">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bKjXiKaBX90|title=Jacko Ali|work=Straight Dialogue|publisher=[[Channel i]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

Ali attended [[Sir John Cass Redcoat School]]. At an early age, he played Junior League football and became the [[Freestyle BMX|BMX Freestyle]] Schoolboy champion. From 1987, at the age of 17, he ran his own fashion design and manufacturing business.<ref name="britbangla"/>

==Kickboxing career==
In 1986, Ali started training as a kickboxer. On 2 December 1990,<ref name="StraightDialogue1"/> he won his first B.I.K.M.A British lightweight kickboxing title. In February 1996, he won the W.M.O European kickboxing title. On 3 October 1999, he won the W.K.N World Inter-Continental Championship. On 26 May 1996, he defeated Frederic Pierre to win the W.K.O World lightweight kickboxing title at The Island in Ilford. In June 2000, Ali took his second World lightweight kickboxing title, this time in the World Kickboxing Network belt.<ref name="britbangla"/><ref name="alijacko"/><ref name="sylhetexpress"/><ref name="StraightDialogue7"/><ref name="dhakacourier">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://groups.google.com/d/msg/soc.culture.bangladesh/HUgJ6uQmmjE/I1x-PmzScTUJ|title=Another Ali another Champion|location=Dhaka|work= |publisher=''[[Dhaka Courier]]''|date=17 January 1998|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref name="cluboops">{{cite web|url=http://www.cluboops.plus.com/cafs/|title=Chamak Ali Foundation UK BD|publisher=Chamak Ali Foundation|date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

Ali became the first Asian to win British, European, Inter-Continental and Work Full-Contact kickboxing championships. He had a 45 fight career,<ref name="britbangla"/> with one defeat by submission due to injury.<ref name="StraightDialogue1"/> Ali's manager and trainer Eddie Dujon took him through his British, European and World Championship fights.<ref name="dhakacourier"/> Ali retired in 2002.<ref name="StraightDialogue1"/>

==Media career==
In July 1997, Ali launched JKO TV, which produces and provides programmes for terrestrial, satellite and corporate clients. It filmed Thai and kickboxing on [[Sky Sports]] and [[Channel 5]].<ref name="britbangla"/><ref name="muaythaionline">{{cite web |url=http://www.muaythaionline.org/fightinfo/jko2003.html|title=Results from Ali Jacko's show|publisher=Muay Thai Online Club|year=2003|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

In June 2000, Ali launched the UK's first all Kick / Thai-boxing magazine ''Kick Boxing UK''.<ref name="prokick">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.prokick.com/archive/archive/HTML/kbnews/kbnewsjun00.htm|title=World Kickboxing News|location= |work= |publisher=''Prokick''|date=June 2000|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

==Awards==
Ali won the Canary Wharf Sporting Personality Award in 2001 and the UK Asian Sporting Award in 2003.<ref name="britbangla"/>

==Personal life==
Ali is a [[Muslim]],<ref name="StraightDialogue7"/> and lives in [[London]]<ref name="cluboops"/> with his wife and<ref name="StraightDialogue7"/> son.<ref name="StraightDialogue5"/><ref name="StraightDialogue6">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d-RlYLzfKOw|title=Jacko Ali|work=StraightDialogue|publisher=[[Channel i]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> His mother lives in Bangladesh.<ref name="StraightDialogue8">{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mgq9VA2zjUQ|title=Jacko Ali|work=StraightDialogue|publisher=[[Channel i]]|date=15 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>

